n width=\"1/2\" css=\".vc_custom_1525449016973{background-color: #ffffff !important;}\"][vc_column_text][contact-form-7 id=\"13\" title=\"Contact form 1\"][/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row][vc_column css=\".vc_custom_1525449022332{background-color: #ffffff !important;}\"][vc_gmaps link=\"#E-8_\"][vc_empty_space][/vc_column][/vc_row]','Contact Us','','publish','closed','closed','','contact','','','2018-09-28 12:36:25','2018-09-28 12:36:25','',0,'http://academy.ftlutte.tn?page_id=157',0,'page','',0),(475,1,'2018-05-05 14:06:02','2018-05-05 14:06:02','','Preview Course','','publish','open','closed','','preview-course','','','2018-05-05 14:06:02','2018-05-05 14:06:02','',0,'http://academy.ftlutte.tncourse/preview-course/',0,'lp_course','',0),(639,2,'2018-07-31 17:34:05','2018-07-31 17:34:05','The course modules are listed on the left. You can view the modules in any order. Some of the modules are completed by a multiple choice exam at the end. The other modules are optional, though you are certainly encouraged to read them.\r\n\r\nYour progress through the course is shown below, both as the number of pages you have read and as your progress towards certification.\r\n\r\nWhen your certificate progress reaches 100%, you can download your certificate of completion.','UWW Ready to Wrestle','','publish','closed','closed','','uww-ready-to-wrestle','','','2018-11-23 08:40:46','2018-11-23 08:40:46','',0,'http://academy.ftlutte.tn/?post_type=lp_course&#038;p=639',0,'lp_course','',0),(642,2,'2018-07-31 17:22:19','2018-07-31 17:22:19','<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-56\" src=\"http://academy.ftlutte.tn/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/cropped-logo-mobile-1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"248\" height=\"94\" /></p>\n&nbsp;\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">United World Wrestling, in partnership with the World Academy of Sport, is initiating a series of educational programmes under the banner of the Wrestling Academy.</p>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">The Wrestling Academy aims to support the development of the sport through competency-based programmes and creates highly trained and knowledgeable personnel, bringing the genuine interest individuals have to coach, teach and practice wrestling. Establishing quality-assured training processes will then produce skilled Educators to then teach these specialized courses and continue the growth of the sport worldwide.</p>','The wrestling academy','','publish','closed','open','','the-wrestling-academy-2','','','2018-07-31 17:22:19','2018-07-31 17:22:19','',0,'http://the-wrestling-academy-2',0,'lp_lesson','',0),(643,2,'2018-07-31 17:22:26','2018-07-31 17:22:26','<h3>Introduction :</h3>\r\nThe United World Wrestling created this platform as a development tool for all affiliated members. The aim of this tool is to share best practices in educational framework and techniques across a range of different methodologies and programmes.\r\n<h3>Key areas of the UWW Academy:</h3>\r\n[list icon=plus\" color=\"accent, dark\"]\r\n\r\n[li]Coach/Referee/Administrators/Educators[/li]\r\n\r\n[li]Online Programmes[/li]\r\n\r\n[li]Group classes[/li]\r\n\r\n[/list]\r\n<h3>Main partners:</h3>\r\n[list icon=square-o\" color=\"accent, dark\"]\r\n\r\n[li]Olympic Solidarity[/li]\r\n\r\n[li]CONFEJES[/li]\r\n\r\n[li]UWW recognised and partner Universities[/li]\r\n\r\n[li]UWW approved training and educational centres[/li]\r\n\r\n[/list]','Academy Partners – World Academy of Sport','','publish','closed','open','','academy-partners-world-academy-of-sport','','','2018-11-23 09:01:58','2018-11-23 09:01:58','',0,'http://academy-partners-world-academy-of-sport',0,'lp_lesson','',0),(644,2,'2018-07-31 17:22:33','2018-07-31 17:22:33','<p id=\"\" class=\"\">The Wrestling Academy Framework consists of a generic introduction followed by three strands of workforce development:</p>\n\n<ul class=\"\">\n 	<li><b>READY to Wrestle</b> – Generic introductory programme for all strands and levels to provide a broad background in the sport and better inform individuals who wish to become involved in wrestling as an athlete or in other ways such as an official, a coach, a parent or even as a supporter</li>\n 	<li><b>Strand 1: Coach education</b> – A programme of online modules and face to face courses from Level 1 (beginner level coach) to Level 3 (international level coach)</li>\n 	<li><b>Strand 2: Officials’ education</b> – A programme of online modules and face-to-face courses for umpires and technical officials</li>\n 	<li><b>Strand 3: Management education</b> – A programme of governance and event management development modules and courses.</li>\n</ul>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">In addition to these three strands, the Wrestling Academy will also encompass all other educational development areas of wrestling at United World Wrestling.</p>','Wrestling Academy Framework','','publish','closed','open','','wrestling-academy-framework','','','2018-07-31 17:22:33','2018-07-31 17:22:33','',0,'http://wrestling-academy-framework',0,'lp_lesson','',0),(645,2,'2018-07-31 17:22:40','2018-07-31 17:22:40','<p id=\"\" class=\"\">The aim of the READY to Wrestle modules is to provide an online education starting point for all wrestling stakeholders.</p>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">The READY to Wrestle programme is a prerequisite for the three strands of the Wrestling Academy programme pathways. It is a general introduction to the different areas of the world of wrestling, including origins of the sport, events, styles, national federations, local clubs, wrestling rules, equipment and development.</p>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">Once you have completed READY to Wrestle, you may then be interested in registering for other more specific technical programmes either to gain more knowledge and assist you in your particular role as a coach, umpire or official, or as a prerequisite to attending a Wrestling Academy face to face programme in the future, a key step to receiving a United World Wrestling certification.</p>','READY to Wrestle online modules','','publish','closed','open','','ready-to-wrestle-online-modules','','','2018-07-31 17:22:40','2018-07-31 17:22:40','',0,'http://ready-to-wrestle-online-modules',0,'lp_lesson','',0),(646,2,'2018-07-31 17:23:09','2018-07-31 17:23:09','<p id=\"\" class=\"\">Wrestling is a sport as old as mankind itself. Since the dawn of time people have been pitted against each other in physical hand-to-hand combat, making this almost certainly the most ancient of Olympic sports.</p>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">It is a simple concept. Two men or women wrestle until one is declared the winner. Over the years, wrestling techniques have become more sophisticated and generally speaking the winner of any wrestling bout is the person who has the better technique, strength and overall fitness.</p>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">Watch the following video. After that, below there is a list of questions to which corresponds one of the answers in the box at the right side. You should drag and drop the right answer to each question.</p>\nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=N_58GH8HpOI&amp;feature=player_embedded\n\n[qsm quiz=1]','What is Wrestling?','','publish','closed','open','','what-is-wrestling','','','2018-07-31 17:23:09','2018-07-31 17:23:09','',0,'http://what-is-wrestling',0,'lp_lesson','',0),(647,2,'2018-07-31 17:23:16','2018-07-31 17:23:16','<p id=\"\" class=\"\">In order to differentiate between the three Olympic wrestling styles, there are 3 easy-to-understand visual clues:</p>\n\n<h3 id=\"\" class=\"\">Opponent’s Body Attack area</h3>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">The main difference between Freestyle (FS) and Greco-Roman (GR) style is the attack contact area of the opponent’s body that is allowed. In Greco-Roman Wrestling, it is strictly forbidden to grasp the opponent below the belt line, while in Freestyle and Women’s wrestling it is permissible to grasp the legs of the opponent.</p>\n                                [highlight bgcolor=\"#2a3333\" color=\"#fff\"]Women\'s[/highlight]                                                        [highlight bgcolor=\"#2a3333\" color=\"#fff\"]Freestyle[/highlight]                                                              [highlight bgcolor=\"#2a3333\" color=\"#fff\"]Greco-Roman[/highlight]\n\n<img class=\"alignleft wp-image-535 size-medium\" src=\"http://academy.ftlutte.tn/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/attack-zones-women-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /> <img class=\"alignright wp-image-533 size-medium\" src=\"http://academy.ftlutte.tn/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/attack-zones-gr-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-534 size-medium\" src=\"http://academy.ftlutte.tn/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/attack-zones-fs-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" />','Differentiating between styles: body attack area','','publish','closed','open','','differentiating-between-styles-body-attack-area','','','2018-07-31 17:23:16','2018-07-31 17:23:16','',0,'http://differentiating-between-styles-body-attack-area',0,'lp_lesson','',0),(648,2,'2018-07-31 17:23:22','2018-07-31 17:23:22','<p id=\"\" class=\"\">In order to differentiate between the three Olympic wrestling styles, there are three easy-to-understand visual clues:</p>\n\n<h3 id=\"\" class=\"\">Stance</h3>\n<ol class=\"\">\n 	<li>Freestyle: in order to be ready to defend a leg attack whilst standing, FS wrestlers spend a lot of time with a low stance, keeping their own legs behind their head, torso and arms. It’s rare to watch the legs of a FS wrestler be too close to the opponent’s legs in the standing position, except during technical actions.</li>\n 	<li>Greco-Roman: in GR the rules encourages the wrestlers to have more contact with the chest and shoulders. Their heads are frequently moving from side to side and they are usually fighting often to place their feet in the best position, even invading the stance position of the other wrestler.</li>\n</ol>','Differentiating between styles: stance','','publish','closed','open','','differentiating-between-styles-stance','','','2018-07-31 17:23:22','2018-07-31 17:23:22','',0,'http://differentiating-between-styles-stance',0,'lp_lesson','',0),(649,2,'2018-07-31 17:23:28','2018-07-31 17:23:28','<p id=\"\" class=\"\">In order to differentiate between the two Olympic wrestling styles, there are 3 easy-to-understand visual clues:<span id=\"edit_link\"></span></p>\n\n<h3 id=\"\" class=\"\">Different techniques<span id=\"edit_link\"></span></h3>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">Moves where the wrestler grabs one or both legs of the opponent, or when the wrestler trips, hooks or blocks the opponents legs by using their own legs, are only allowed in FS. In GR, since wrestlers are not allowed to attack or defend using legs, the so called “lifts” from the ground and some upper body throws from standing are more frequently seen and more useful than in FS.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><iframe src=\"https://player.vimeo.com/video/168308676\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe></p>','Differentiating between styles: technique','','publish','closed','open','','differentiating-between-styles-technique','','','2018-07-31 17:23:28','2018-07-31 17:23:28','',0,'http://differentiating-between-styles-technique',0,'lp_lesson','',0),(650,2,'2018-07-31 17:23:37','2018-07-31 17:23:37','<p id=\"\" class=\"\">There are two main ways to win a wrestling match.</p>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">The ultimate goal in wrestling is the so called ‘fall’ or sometimes called \'pin\'. This is a situation when the defensive wrestler is held by his opponent with his two shoulder blades touching the mat for a sufficient time to allow the referee to observe the total control of this position. If the opponent rolls over on their back, or if both shoulders are not against the mat at the same time, this is not a fall. The shoulder blades must being ‘pinned’ at the same time.</p>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">A fall leads to the absolute victory for the wrestler who puts his/her opponent in such a situation. This is the equivalent to a knockout in boxing: the match ends when a fall is confirmed by the umpires.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><iframe src=\"https://player.vimeo.com/video/168308678\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe></p>\n&nbsp;\n\nWrestlers over the age of 18 have six minutes in total to pin their opponent’s shoulders blades, which is split in two 3-minute periods with a 30 second break. Since the defence of the wrestlers is aimed to avoid the fall, if the wrestlers do not achieve the pin at the end of the ruled time, the second way to win is scoring more points than the opponent.','How to win','','publish','closed','open','','how-to-win','','','2018-07-31 17:23:37','2018-07-31 17:23:37','',0,'http://how-to-win',0,'lp_lesson','',0),(651,2,'2018-07-31 17:23:43','2018-07-31 17:23:43','<p id=\"\" class=\"\">To score points, wrestlers should force and take the opponent down to the mat and work for pinning her/him. There are two main control positions to score points.</p>\n\n<h3 id=\"\" class=\"\">Danger position</h3>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">This consists in exposing the opponent’s back to the mat, ‘in danger to be pinned’. The wrestler is in the Danger Position when his/her back is forming less than a 90° angle in relation to the horizontal line of the mat. This situation is valid even if it lasts only an instant, or if the opponent is rolling over their own hands, elbows or head.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><iframe src=\"https://player.vimeo.com/video/168308677\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe></p>\n\n<h3 id=\"\" class=\"\">Par-Terre</h3>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">In order to avoid being pinned when they are taken down to the ground, wrestlers can turn themselves to face the mat or land prone over their hands and knees (facing the mat, out of the danger position). In these cases, the attacking wrestler often gets a top position behind the controlled opponent. This position is called Par-Terre, French term which means \"on the ground\". The top wrestler can continue attacking from this position.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><iframe src=\"https://player.vimeo.com/video/170449972\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe></p>\n&nbsp;\n\nWrestlers can force their opponent to these positions and score points by <b>executing techniques</b>. The more techniques a wrestler executes, the most points scored.','How to score','','publish','closed','open','','how-to-score','','','2018-07-31 17:23:43','2018-07-31 17:23:43','',0,'http://how-to-score',0,'lp_lesson','',0),(652,2,'2018-07-31 17:23:49','2018-07-31 17:23:49','<p id=\"\" class=\"\">Wrestling techniques are series of movements, controls and maneuvers aimed to score points by forcing the opponent to expose the back (danger position) or to take the top spot in the \'behind control position\' on the ground.</p>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">Many of these techniques can be stopped and counterattacked by other techniques. So, the points are scored only if the technique was successful regarding the mentioned control positions.</p>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">How many points a technique is worth depends on what control position was achieved and from which position it started.</p>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">Generally speaking, wrestlers can score from two different wrestling positions: <b>standing</b> and <b><i>par-terre</i></b>, this last term is a French expression that means “on the ground”.</p>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">When a wrestler accomplishes one of such goals, the umpire immediately raises one of his/her hands showing as many fingers as points the technique is worth. There are 2 point and 4 point techniques for both wrestling styles. 5 points are given only for grand amplitude throws in Greco-Roman.</p>\n\n<h3 id=\"\" class=\"\">How to score 2 points</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><iframe src=\"https://player.vimeo.com/video/168179128\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe></p>\n\n<h3 id=\"\" class=\"\">How to score 4 points</h3>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><iframe src=\"https://player.vimeo.com/video/168308673\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe></p>\n\n<h3 id=\"\" class=\"\">How to score 5 points</h3>\nhttps://player.vimeo.com/video/223436127\n\n&nbsp;','Wrestling Techniques','','publish','closed','open','','wrestling-techniques','','','2018-07-31 17:23:49','2018-07-31 17:23:49','',0,'http://wrestling-techniques',0,'lp_lesson','',0),(653,2,'2018-07-31 17:23:55','2018-07-31 17:23:55','<p id=\"\" class=\"\">Wrestling is probably the safest sport among the combat disciplines, since its goal is to win control of the opponent’s body, without striking, choking or causing pain to achieve submission. Advanced, high performance wrestlers are able to bout almost every day in the training environment, whilst many other combat sports are not characterised by such amount of fun!</p>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">But this is possible not just due the nature of the sport, but also thanks to the involvement of coaches, parents, organisations and wrestlers themselves to ensure safety in wrestling.</p>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">To prevent medical issues, physical examination prior to joining a wrestling club is possibly the most important step. Coaches can plan long term physical conditioning as well as the complexity of teaching progression and periodical equipment and facility inspections for the prevention of injuries. Also, there are critical daily habits for wrestlers and coaches during practices such as initial warm-up routines to prepare the whole body, and to establish and observe safety rules.</p>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">A particularly important task for wrestling coaches is ensuring that athlete\'s match-ups are appropriate, and based on size, strength, level of skill, experience, in order to reduce the risk of injury. This should be a particular focus during early development stages, and when the individuals who are composing the group have different levels and body weights, or if the group is a mixture of women and men. As girls and boys go through growth spurts during adolescence it is important to continually monitor the group and ensure athletes are practising with similar ability and weight.</p>','Safety','','publish','closed','open','','safety','','','2018-07-31 17:23:55','2018-07-31 17:23:55','',0,'http://safety',0,'lp_lesson','',0),(654,2,'2018-07-31 17:24:01','2018-07-31 17:24:01','<p id=\"\" class=\"\">A common aspect among combat sports is their main goal to win is to not allow the opponent to act. In wrestling unlike some other combat sports the goal is not to harm the opponent such as in boxing nor symbolically injure your opponent as in fencing.</p>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">In this sense wrestling is one of the safest combat sports. Wrestlers should prove their ability and technical superiority by grabbing and locking the opponent and then get the fall using their whole body. Physical capabilities such as strength, flexibility and endurance throughout the match, using an amazing amount of different moves, takedowns and body turn techniques are essential. No intentional injury nor infliction of pain is allowed or encouraged by the wrestling rules. This characteristic of wrestling rules ensures that wrestlers can wrestle safely in every practice, in every session, and take part in many tournaments throughout the season which means lots of fun!</p>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">Physical features such as height and limb length become important factors for wrestlers to choose and master different strategies and techniques match after match. This is due to the fact that wrestlers are paired by body weight and considering that wrestlers are paired by body weight, physical features (i.e. height and limb length) are not limiting in wrestling – on the contrary, every wrestler can choose different strategies based in the mixture of features match after match. In wrestling, the saying is “everybody can wrestle!”</p>','What can you do?','','publish','closed','open','','what-can-you-do','','','2018-07-31 17:24:01','2018-07-31 17:24:01','',0,'http://what-can-you-do',0,'lp_lesson','',0),(655,2,'2018-07-31 17:24:07','2018-07-31 17:24:07','<p id=\"\" class=\"\">Wrestlers are trained to dominate the opponent by grips, locks and moves avoiding risky leverages and dangerous joint movements. Some examples include elbow leverages, grasping fingers, and forcing lower back hyperextensions. They are allowed to attempt neck holds provided that one arm is between the lock, in order to ensure protection to the wrestler’s neck and to avoid chokes. Moreover, in the neck and arm control situations theif attacking wrestler has their opponent in immediate danger and does not execute a safe technique immediately the umpire will stop the action to avoid chokes.</p>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">Depending on the wrestling style, any form of tie-up and grip is permitted, except if its intention is to cause pain or injury. An exception to this is to touch or grab the opponent’s face between the eyebrows and lips, nor the grabbing of the opponent\'s clothing. Touching and grabbing the wrestler’s chin, forehead and the back of the head are however valid moves.</p>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">Needless to say, all form of hitting or striking the opponent is not allowed, not only with fists but with any part of the body. Finally wrestlers cannot apply any greasy or sticky substances to their body or arrive at the mat perspiring at the beginning of the match nor for the beginning of each period.</p>','What can you NOT do?','','publish','closed','open','','what-can-you-not-do','','','2018-07-31 17:24:07','2018-07-31 17:24:07','',0,'http://what-can-you-not-do',0,'lp_lesson','',0),(656,2,'2018-07-31 17:24:13','2018-07-31 17:24:13','<p id=\"\" class=\"\">As a person develops it is important that their sport programme evolves to continually engage and challenge them throughout their life. There has been much work undertaken in understanding the development needs of individuals and how sport and exercise plays an important role throughout life.</p>\r\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">For coaches, the LTAD becomes important in understanding what skills should be taught at what development stage. This also means that the coach understands that the athletes being trained can be the same age, but in different developmental stages. Coaches must be aware of their athletes and the stage of their individual development.</p>\r\n<img class=\"size-full wp-image-718 aligncenter\" src=\"http://academy.ftlutte.tn/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/wrestling-athlete-pathway-en.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"800\" height=\"739\" />\r\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">The above model is a generic LTAD. Several National Federations have developed wrestling specific models, such as <a href=\"https://wrestling.ca/programs/long-term-athlete-development\">Wrestling Canada</a>.</p>\r\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">For coaches the LTAD becomes important in understanding what skills should be taught at what development stage an individual is at. For managers and administrators of wrestling this model is considered in the broader context of the National Federation and what is needed to sustain a successful athlete pathway.</p>\r\n\r\n<div></div>','Athlete pathway','','publish','closed','open','','v','','','2018-11-20 12:36:49','2018-11-20 12:36:49','',0,'http://v',0,'lp_lesson','',0),(658,2,'2018-07-31 17:24:38','2018-07-31 17:24:38','<p class=\"\">Wrestling is one of the oldest sports, and there are many references in documents and paintings that date thousands of years ago. From the Sumerians, to the Ancient Egypt, Ancient Greece, Middle Ages and Renaissance wrestling competitions has been a really popular among different civilisations. In the XIX century professional wrestling emerged prior to the revival of the Modern Olympics.</p>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">The following list is expandable. Clicking or tapping on either a heading or a date will expand that section to provide more detailed information. This is the case with all timelines in this programme.</p>\n[collapsibles]\n[collapse title=\"Sumerians\" active=\"true\"]\n<div id=\"\" class=\"timeline-wrapper\" title=\"\">\n<h5><strong>5000 B.C.</strong><img class=\"size-full wp-image-720 alignright\" src=\"http://academy.ftlutte.tn/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/summerians-trophy.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"250\" height=\"332\" /></h5>\nThe first real traces of the development of wrestling date back to the time of the Sumerians, 5000 years ago. The Epic of Gilgamesh written in cuneiform, the sculptures and the low reliefs ar\n\ne numerous sources that reveal the first umpired competitions. A bronze sculpture, discovered at Khafaji, near Baghdad and nowadays on display in Baghdad Museum, shows two wrestlers grip each other by the belt. Made around 2,800 B.C., it is the oldest representation of ritual wrestling of which we have knowledge¹.\n\n</div>\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n<p style=\"text-align: right;\">[highlight]A bronze sculpture, discovered at Khafaji,\nnear Baghdad and now displayed in the National Museum of Iraq,\nshows two wrestlers gripping each other by the belt.[/highlight]</p>\n\n<h2 id=\"\" class=\"timeline-time\"></h2>\n[/collapse]\n[collapse title=\"Ancient Egypt\"]\n<h5><strong>2100 B.C.</strong></h5>\nThere are also many historical and archaeological traces of wrestling in <b>Ancient Egypt</b> with tombs representing around 400 pairs of wrestlers painted around 2100 B.C. These drawings, as well as many other vestiges, witness the existence of organised wrestling in Ancient Egypt, wrestling rules and umpiring codes.\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-721\" src=\"http://academy.ftlutte.tn/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/egypt-tomb-wide.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"600\" height=\"267\" />\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-722\" src=\"http://academy.ftlutte.tn/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/egypt-tomb-close.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"356\" height=\"267\" />\n[highlight]Images of the Tombs of Baqet and Khety, located in Beni Hasan, Egypt. [/highlight]\n\n[/collapse]\n[collapse title=\"Ancient Greece\"]\n<h5><strong>800 B.C.</strong></h5>\nThe <b>ancient Greek</b> wrestling schools were called <b>palaestra</b> (from Greek παλαίστρα –palaistra-, textually \"wrestling place”). The palaestra functioned both independently and as a part of the public gymnasium; a palaestra could exist without a gymnasium, but no gymnasium could exist without a palaestra². For the Greeks, wrestling was a science and a divine art, and it represented the most important training for young men. Athletes wrestled naked, with their bodies coated with olive oil and covered with a layer of very thin sand to protect the skin from sunlight or from cold during winter³.\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-723\" src=\"http://academy.ftlutte.tn/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/ancient-greek-wrestlers.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"500\" height=\"207\" />\n[highlight]Base of a statue representing two wrestlers, Relief of Marble, 510 B.C., National Archeological Museum, Athens.[/highlight]\n\n[/collapse]\n\n[collapse title=\"Olympic Games\"]\n<h5><strong>708 B.C.</strong>\n<strong>393 A.D.</strong><span id=\"edit_link\"></span><span id=\"edit_link\"></span></h5>\n<div id=\"\" class=\"\" title=\"\">\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">The Olympic Games lasted, uninterrupted for almost 1,200 years, before Emperor Theodosius I imposed the ban. In 393 Emperor Theodosius I prohibited all pagan festivities, thus, he outlawed the Olympic Games because the Games were celebrated in honor of Zeus.</p>\n\n</div>\n<h5><strong>100-200 A.D.</strong></h5>\n<div id=\"\" class=\"\" title=\"\">\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">From this time came the most ancient written document ever found with instructions to practice and compete in any sport: a papyrus scroll dated 100-200 A.D. with rules to wrestle and the description of certain techniques⁴.</p>\n\n</div>\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-724\" src=\"http://academy.ftlutte.tn/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/papyrus.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"400\" height=\"288\" />\n[highlight]The papyrus Oxyrhynchus 466[/highlight]\n\n[/collapse]\n\n[collapse title=\"Middle Ages &amp; Renaissance\"]\n<h5><strong>1512</strong><span id=\"edit_link\"></span><span id=\"edit_link\"></span></h5>\n<div id=\"\" class=\"\" title=\"\">\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">During the <b>Middle Ages</b> and <b>Renaissance</b>, wrestling was practiced by the social elite, in castles and palaces.</p>\nA remarkable document is the book Oplodidaskalia sive Armorvm Tractandorvm Meditatio Alberti Dvreri (“Weapon Training, or Albrecht Dürer\'s Meditation on the Handling of Weapons”), published in 1512 and illustrated by Dürer. This 127 page book is considered a handbook of hand weapons (longsword, dagger and messer), with its first 40 color, illustrated pages about wrestling (unarmed) techniques⁵. This book illustrated by Dürer its considered the very first wrestling printed handbook.\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-725\" src=\"http://academy.ftlutte.tn/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/durer-illustrations.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"800\" height=\"381\" />\n[highlight]Illustrations of wrestling techniques and holds made by Albrecht Dürer.[/highlight]\n\n</div>\n[/collapse]\n\n[collapse title=\"Modern Greco-Roman Wrestling\"]\n<h5><strong>1830</strong><span id=\"edit_link\"></span></h5>\n<div id=\"\" class=\"\" title=\"\">\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">Despite its name, Greco-Roman wrestling was not a style practised in the ancient Greek-Roman times, but a creation of XIX century professional wrestling prior to the revival of the Modern Olympics.<span id=\"edit_link\"></span></p>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">Around <b>1830</b>, professional wrestling began in France, where wrestlers who had no access to the wrestling elite, formed troupes that travelled around France displaying their talent.</p>\n\n</div>\n<h5><strong>1848</strong></h5>\n<div id=\"\" class=\"\" title=\"\">\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">In <b>1848</b>, French showman Jean Exbroyat created the first modern wrestlers’ circus troupe and established a rule not to execute holds below the waist. He named this new style flat hand wrestling. Upon Mr. Exbroyat’s death in 1872, Mr. Rossignol-Rollin attorney from Lyon assumed the direction of this troupe and was soon noticed for his ability to advertise, to arrange matches and to reward wrestlers in the name of the audience.</p>\n\n</div>\n[/collapse]\n[/collapsibles]\n<div id=\"\" class=\"\" title=\"\">\n<div id=\"\" class=\"\" title=\"\">\n<h4 id=\"\" class=\"\">References</h4>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\"><sup>1</sup> Piernavieja del Pozo, Miguel (1973). “Wrestling in Antiquity”, in Olympic Review, September-October No. 70-71 p. 412-424., retrieved from</p>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\"><a href=\"http://library.la84.org/OlympicInformationCenter/OlympicReview/1973/ore70/ore70k.pdf\">http://library.la84.org/OlympicInformationCenter/OlympicReview/1973/ore70/ore70k.pdf</a></p>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\"><sup>2 </sup><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Palaestra\">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Palaestra</a></p>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\"><sup>3 </sup>N.P.Goulandris Foundation - Museum of Cycladic Art (2004). Travelling with Glaukos to Olympia in 476 BC, Athens, p. 18. Retrieved from</p>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\"><a href=\"http://www.altsys.gr/uploads/docs/ALTSYS_MKT_GLAUKOS_en.pdf\">http://www.altsys.gr/uploads/docs/ALTSYS_MKT_GLAUKOS_en.pdf</a></p>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\"><sup>4 </sup><a href=\"http://wwwapp.cc.columbia.edu\">http://wwwapp.cc.columbia.edu</a></p>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\"><sup>5</sup> <a href=\"http://wiktenauer.com/wiki/\">http://wiktenauer.com/wiki/</a></p>\n\n</div>\n</div>','Ancient traditions','','publish','closed','open','','ancient-traditions','','','2018-07-31 17:24:38','2018-07-31 17:24:38','',0,'http://ancient-traditions',0,'lp_lesson','',0),(659,2,'2018-07-31 17:24:45','2018-07-31 17:24:45','Match the facts with their corresponding date on the time line of wrestling facts.\n\n[qsm quiz=2]','Ancient traditions - activity','','publish','closed','closed','','ancient-traditions-activity','','','2018-07-31 17:24:45','2018-07-31 17:24:45','',0,'http://ancient-traditions-activity',0,'lp_lesson','',0),(660,2,'2018-07-31 17:24:53','2018-07-31 17:24:53','At the first Modern Olympic Games in 1896, wrestling was one of the most popular and important sports. In the Athens 1896 Olympic Games only <b>Greco-Roman style wrestling</b> was included. During the St. Louis 1904 Olympic games <b>Freestyle wrestling</b> was introduced. With the occasion of the Athens 2004 Olympic Games <b>women wrestling</b> was introduced as an Olympic discipline.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[collapsibles]\n[collapse title=\"Restoration of Olympism\" active=\"true\"]\n<h5><strong>1894</strong><span id=\"edit_link\"></span></h5>\n<div id=\"\" class=\"\" title=\"\">\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">After the creation of the International Olympic Committee by <b>Baron Pierre de Coubertin</b> in 1894, the development of new International Sport Federations and National Olympic Committees increased. The first Olympic Congress took place in 1894 at « la Sorbonne » and decided on the ten sports that would be part of the first modern Olympic program: athletics, wrestling, rowing, cycling, fencing, gymnastics, weightlifting, swimming, shooting and tennis.</p>\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-728\" src=\"http://academy.ftlutte.tn/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/decoubertin.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"585\" height=\"263\" />\n[highlight]Pierre de Fréddy, Baron de Coubertin (right). In the group (left), taken at the IOC Session in Athens in April 1896, Coubertin is second from the left.[/highlight]\n<h5><strong>1896</strong></h5>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">During the first Olympic Games of the modern era, held in <b>Athens (1896)</b>, the wrestling tournament did not include weight categories and all five competitors wrestled under rules similar to those of the professional Greco-Roman wrestling (grips and tie-ups only to the upper body). The matches lasted until one of the competitors won without any time limit.</p>\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-729\" src=\"http://academy.ftlutte.tn/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/1896-final.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"800\" height=\"560\" />\n[highlight]Carl Schuhmann (left) and Georgios Tsitas shake hands before the final match of the 1896 wrestling competition.[/highlight]\n<h5><strong>1898</strong></h5>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">The French influence extended to the Austrian Hungarian Empire, from Italy, to Denmark and Russia under the new style and name of Greco-Roman wrestling. In 1898, the Frenchman Paul Pons was the first Professional World Champion, and was followed by Ladislaus Pytlasinski from Poland. Other great champions from this period include the Turkish Kara Ahmed, the Bulgarian Nikola Petrov and Ukranian Ivan Poddubni.</p>\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-730\" src=\"http://academy.ftlutte.tn/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/poddubni.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"350\" height=\"498\" />\n[highlight]Ivan Poddubni. In Modern Russia, there is an annual,\ntough international wrestling tournament in his honor.[/highlight]\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<img class=\"size-full wp-image-731 alignnone\" src=\"http://academy.ftlutte.tn/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/poddubni-grip.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"179\" height=\"274\" />\n[highlight]Ivan Poddubni executing a classic hold\nto the upper body of his opponent in ‘classic wrestling’.[/highlight]\n\n</div>\n<div title=\"\"></div>\n<div title=\"\"><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wg7SlZ_qZGM&amp;feature=youtu.be\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wg7SlZ_qZGM&amp;feature=youtu.be</a></div>\n<div title=\"\">Some drills of early Greco-Roman movements</div>\n<div title=\"\"></div>\n<h5><strong>1900</strong></h5>\n<div title=\"\">\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">At the end of the 19th century, professional wrestling was the most in vogue sport in Europe, but it started to degrade from 1900 because of the pre-arranged matches, the announcement of forgery, false victories and false nationalities of the competitors. The rediscovery of Olympic amateurism encouraged the creation of numerous clubs and schools that led to the demise of professional wrestling, but provided a way for many more people to participate in wrestling.</p>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">In Paris, in 1900, and for this unique occasion in the history of the modern Olympic Games, the Games did not include wrestling in their program, even though at the same time, professional wrestling was at its best shape at the Folies Bergères and the Casino de Paris.</p>\n\n</div>\n[/collapse]\n[collapse title=\"Modern Olympic Wrestling\"]\n<div title=\"\">\n<h5><strong>1904</strong></h5>\n<div class=\"request-edit\">\n<p id=\"\" class=\"floatleft\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-732 alignright\" src=\"http://academy.ftlutte.tn/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/poster-1904.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"200\" height=\"309\" />During the III Olympic Games held in St. Louis 1904, <b>freestyle wrestling</b> was first introduced, being only contested by American wrestlers. It was only during the IV Olympic Games held in London in 1908 that competitions were organized for both styles.</p>\n&nbsp;\n\n</div>\n</div>\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n<h5><strong>1912</strong></h5>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"floatleft\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-733 alignright\" src=\"http://academy.ftlutte.tn/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/stockholm-1912.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"585\" height=\"480\" />At the Stockholm Olympic Games in 1912, freestyle wrestling was again absent from the program and glima competitions (Icelandic wrestling) were organized. The match which confronted the Finnish wrestler Alfred Johan Asikainen and the Russian Martin Klein lasted 11 hours and 40 minutes and appears on the Guinness Book of Records.</p>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"floatleft\">From this date, and encouraged by the newly created International Federation, wrestling developed in every country. Northern Europe countries maintained during many years the monopoly of Greco-Roman wrestling, whereas freestyle wrestling was largely dominated by the English and the Americans.</p>\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n<p id=\"\" class=\"caption\" style=\"text-align: right;\">[highlight]Alfred Johan Asikanen and Martin Klein wrestle in the Stockholm 1912 Olympics in\nthe match which holds the world record for the longest ever.[/highlight]</p>\n\n<h5><strong>1987</strong></h5>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">It is known that women have practiced wrestling at club and national level in certain countries since mid XX century. Thanks to its growing popularity in Europe and Asia, the very first World Wrestling Championships for women run by the international body in charge of the sport of wrestling was held on 1987 in Lorenskog, Norway, in 9 weight categories.</p>\n\n<h5><strong>2004</strong></h5>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">A hundred years after the introduction of freestyle wrestling in the Olympic program, worldwide wrestling entered a new era with the acknowledgement of <b>women wrestling</b> as an Olympic discipline on the occasion of the <b>Athens Olympic Games</b> in 2004. This decision is part of the policy of the IOC that aims at establishing equality in sport, and legitimized the efforts made to the development of women wrestling since the end of the 1980s. The tournament was convened in 4 weight categories, whose gold medals were taken by Irini Merleni-Melnik, from Ukraine, in 48 kg, the japaneses Saorí Yoshida (55 kg) and Kaori Icho (63), and the Chinese Xu Wang in 75 kg.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><iframe src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/LURGSZN0bpE\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe></p>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"caption\">[highlight]Irina Merleni (UKR) winning the First Olympic Gold in women Wrestling, Olympic Games in Athens 2004[highlight]</p>\n\n<h5><strong>2016</strong></h5>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">At the Rio 2016 Olympic Games the Women\'s Freestyle Wrestling event will expand from four weight categories to six. Men’s wrestlers will be competing in six weight categories in the Freestyle Wrestling and the Greco-Roman Wrestling events.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><iframe src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/ZuF0QdQgkBs\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">[/collapse]\n[/collapsibles]</p>\n\n<h2 id=\"\" class=\"timeline-time\"></h2>\n<div title=\"\">\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\"></p>\n\n</div>\n<div title=\"\">\n<h2 id=\"\" class=\"timeline-time\"></h2>\n</div>\n&nbsp;','Wrestling and the Olympics','','publish','closed','open','','wrestling-and-the-olympics','','','2018-07-31 17:24:53','2018-07-31 17:24:53','',0,'http://wrestling-and-the-olympics',0,'lp_lesson','',0),(661,2,'2018-07-31 17:24:59','2018-07-31 17:24:59','<p id=\"\" class=\"\">Pair the Olympic posters with the corresponding wrestling style .</p>\n[qsm quiz=3]','Modern Olympic Wrestling - activity','','publish','closed','open','','modern-olympic-wrestling-activity','','','2018-07-31 17:24:59','2018-07-31 17:24:59','',0,'http://modern-olympic-wrestling-activity',0,'lp_lesson','',0),(662,2,'2018-07-31 17:25:05','2018-07-31 17:25:05','<p id=\"\" class=\"\"><img class=\"wp-image-740 size-medium alignright\" src=\"http://academy.ftlutte.tn/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/top-golds-2017-300x300.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"300\" />Numerous legends shaped the history of Olympic wrestling around the world and it would be impossible to name them all<sup>2</sup> .</p>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">However, it is worth highlighting the eight wrestlers who so far have deeply changed the history of the Modern Olympic Games by winning three or more Olympic titles:</p>\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[table-wrap bordered=\"true\" striped=\"true\"]\n<table class=\"tablewrapper\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><header>NAME</header></td>\n<td><header>COUNTRY</header></td>\n<td><header>STYLE - YEARS</header></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><b>Carl Westergren</b></td>\n<td>Sweden</td>\n<td>Greco-Roman in 1920, 1924 and 1932</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><b>Ivar Johansson</b></td>\n<td>Sweden</td>\n<td>Freestyle in 1932 and 1936, Greco-Roman in 1932</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><b>Alexandre Medved</b></td>\n<td>Former U.S.S.R. (born in Belarus)</td>\n<td>Freestyle in 1964, 1968 and 1972</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><b>Alexander Karelin</b></td>\n<td>Former U.S.S.R. / Russia</td>\n<td>Greco-Roman in 1988, 1992 and 1996\nMijain López\nCuba\nGreco-Roman in 2008, 2012 and 2016</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><b>Bouvaisar Saitiev</b></td>\n<td>Russia</td>\n<td>Freestyle in 1996, 2004 and 2008</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><b>Mijain López</b></td>\n<td>Cuba</td>\n<td>Greco-Roman in 2008, 2012 and 2016</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><b>Saori Yoshida</b></td>\n<td>Japan</td>\n<td>Women wrestling in 2004, 2008 and 2012</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><b>Kaori Icho</b></td>\n<td>Japan</td>\n<td>Women wrestling in 2004, 2008, 2012 and 2016</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n[/table-wrap]\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">After obtaining his third title, <b>Alexander Karelin<sup>3</sup> </b>decided to compete for a fourth title at the Olympic Games in Sydney in 2000, but to general surprise, he was beaten by the American wrestler <b>Rulon Gardner</b>.</p>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">In 2002, during the World Championship held in Moscow, two men were awarded the Best Wrestlers of the Century. Both men were Russians with only one awarded this title per style: <b>Alexander Medved</b> for freestyle wrestling and <b>Alexander Karelin</b> for Greco-roman wrestling, offering them the “Gold Necklace”, an award generally reserved for heads of state.</p>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">In Women Wrestling <b>Saori Yoshida<sup>1</sup> </b>features in the Guinness World Records as the most decorated wrestler ever (including men), by winning 16 World Titles in a row (two in Cadet 17-18 years old age category, two more in Junior 19-20 years old, and 12 more as a Senior, as well as Four Olympic Medals from 2004 to 2016 (3 Golds and 1 Silver). Her countrywoman <b>Kaori Icho</b>, 10-time World Champion, is the top Olympic Title winner in wrestling history (4 titles in a row from 2004 to 2016) and the first woman ever to win a gold medal in individual events at four different Olympic Games<sup>4</sup>.</p>\n\n<h4 id=\"\" class=\"\">References</h4>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\"><a href=\"http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/news/2012/10/worlds-oldest-living-man-welcomes-guinness-world-records-editor-to-his-home-45453\">http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/news/2012/10/worlds-oldest-living-man-welcomes-guinness-world-records-editor-to-his-home-45453</a></p>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\"><a href=\"http://www.apimages.com/metadata/Index/Guinness-cites-wrestler-Yoshida-for-15-straight-world-titles/aa04aa6b4caa4e2db6cc4b12729411b2\">http://www.apimages.com/metadata/Index/Guinness-cites-wrestler-Yoshida-for-15-straight-world-titles/aa04aa6b4caa4e2db6cc4b12729411b2</a></p>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\"><a href=\"https://www.iat.uni-leipzig.de/datenbanken/dbfoeldeak/daten.php?spid=03DC0277598941BDBC3228FB2E080255\">https://www.iat.uni-leipzig.de/datenbanken/dbfoeldeak/daten.php?spid=03DC0277598941BDBC3228FB2E080255</a></p>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\"><a href=\"http://edition.cnn.com/2016/08/17/sport/kaori-icho-wrestling-rio/\">http://edition.cnn.com/2016/08/17/sport/kaori-icho-wrestling-rio/</a></p>\n\n<h4 id=\"\" class=\"\">Videos</h4>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\"><sup>1</sup> <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FIhniPTXvcw\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FIhniPTXvcw</a></p>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\"><sup>2</sup> <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QtTEw1-bcBw&amp;list=PL-292yfpAFGZeXXpJ3V8ZeqW4g_887hJ9&amp;index=10\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QtTEw1-bcBw&amp;list=PL-292yfpAFGZeXXpJ3V8ZeqW4g_887hJ9&amp;index=10</a></p>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\"><sup>3</sup> <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AfFTFN6Y3Us\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AfFTFN6Y3Us</a></p>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\"><sup>4 </sup><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ziD-cpGlTTY\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ziD-cpGlTTY</a></p>\n\n<div></div>\n<div class=\"buttonwrapper3\"></div>\n&nbsp;','Legends of the modern Olympic Games','','publish','closed','open','','legends-of-the-modern-olympic-games','','','2018-07-31 17:25:05','2018-07-31 17:25:05','',0,'http://legends-of-the-modern-olympic-games',0,'lp_lesson','',0),(663,2,'2018-07-31 17:25:15','2018-07-31 17:25:15','<div id=\"\" class=\"floatright\" title=\"\"><img id=\"\" class=\"img  alignright\" title=\"\" src=\"https://www.unitedworldwrestling.academy/images/courses/97/milon.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></div>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">The most famous of all Greek wrestlers was <b>Milon of Croton</b>, student of the philosopher Pythagoras, six times Olympic champion (from 540 to 516 B.C.), ten times winner of the Isthmic Games, nine times winner of the Nemean Games, and five times winner of the Pythic Games. The legend tells that he developed his enormous strength since his childhood by lifting and carrying a newborn calf and repeating the feat daily as it grew to maturity<sup>6</sup>.</p>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\">The demigod <b>Heracles</b> was the patron and protector of gymnasia and palaestra. Heracles was described as a divine hero, son of Zeus and a mortal queen. Known in Rome and the modern West as Hercules, and owner of extraordinary strength and courage. According to the myth, a nemesis of Hercules was Antaeus who was indefatigably strong and immortal as long as he remained in contact with the ground (his mother earth). Heracles, realizing this, changed his strategy and killed Antaeus by lifting him up and holding him in the air until asphyxiation.</p>\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n<p style=\"text-align: right;\">\n[highlight]Artistic depiction of Milon[/highlight]</p>\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-799\" src=\"http://academy.ftlutte.tn/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/foundation-of-hercules.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"585\" height=\"391\" />\n[highlight]The fountain of Hercules and Antaeus, by Niccolo Tribolo (located at Villa di Castello’s Gardens, Florence, Tuscany, central Italy)[/highlight]\n<h4 id=\"\" class=\"\">References</h4>\n<p id=\"\" class=\"\"><sup>6</sup> Chiras, Daniel (2005). Human biology (5 ed.). Jones &amp; Bartlett Publishers. p. 229.</p>','Ancient legends','','publish','closed','open','','legends-of-the-modern-olympic-games-2','','','2018-07-31 17:25:15','2018-07-31 17:25:15','',0,'http://legends-of-the-modern-olympic-games-2',0,'lp_lesson','',0),(665,2,'2018-07-31 17:25:26','2018-07-31 17:25:26','<h3><strong>AFRICA</strong></h3>\n&nbsp;\n\nIsabella Sambou (Senegal) [highlight]<a href=\"https://unitedworldwrestling.org/article/isabelle-sambou-inspires-women-of-senegal\">Feature article</a>[/highlight]\n\nIbrahim Moustafa (Egypt) [highlight]<a href=\"https://www.iat.uni-leipzig.de/datenbanken/dbfoeldeak/daten.php?spid=3BF87A14CE6E442484351268F9C92DAE\">Database</a>[/highlight]\n\nDaniel Igali (Nigeria-Canada) [highlight]<a href=\"https://unitedworldwrestling.org/person/baraladei-daniel-igali\">Profile</a>[/highlight]\n<h3></h3>\n<h3><strong>AMERICAS</strong></h3>\n&nbsp;\n\nDan Gable (USA) [highlight]<a href=\"http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ga/dan-gable-1.html\">Biography</a>[/highlight]\n\nBruce Baumgartner (USA) [highlight]<a href=\"https://unitedworldwrestling.org/person/bruce-baumgartner\">Profile</a>[/highlight]\n\nJohn Smith (USA) [highlight]<a href=\"https://unitedworldwrestling.o